When you use a Web-based loader (like WebBaseLoader), you are fetching data from the internet, which is the most unpredictable source of all. Websites change their structure, headers, and metadata constantly.
Using Pydantic here ensures that even if a website’s title is missing or its "language" tag is weird, your ingestion pipeline stays consistent.
1. The Pydantic Schema for Web Data
We’ll define a schema that standardizes what we want from a webpage. We’ll even use a validator to ensure the URL is clean.
from pydantic import BaseModel, HttpUrl, Field, field_validator
from typing import Optional

class WebPageMetadata(BaseModel):
    source: HttpUrl                   # Validates that it's a real URL
    title: str = "Untitled Page"      # Default value if title is missing
    language: str = "en"              # Standardize language code
    word_count: int = Field(default=0, ge=0) 

    @field_validator('language')
    @classmethod
    def clean_language(cls, v: str) -> str:
        # Standardize 'en-US' or 'English' to just 'en'
        if 'en' in v.lower():
            return 'en'
        return v.lower()

2. Ingesting with WebBaseLoader
The WebBaseLoader pulls the HTML and converts it into a LangChain Document. We then wrap that document in our Pydantic guardrail.
from langchain_community.document_loaders import WebBaseLoader

# 1. Load the webpage
loader = WebBaseLoader("https://example.com")
docs = loader.load()

valid_web_docs = []

for doc in docs:
    # 2. Extract raw metadata provided by the loader
    raw_meta = {
        "source": doc.metadata.get("source"),
        "title": doc.metadata.get("title"),
        "language": doc.metadata.get("language", "en"),
        "word_count": len(doc.page_content.split())
    }
    
    try:
        # 3. Validate and Clean
        validated_meta = WebPageMetadata(**raw_meta)
        
        # 4. Update the document with the clean model
        doc.metadata = validated_meta.model_dump()
        valid_web_docs.append(doc)
        
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Skipping page due to bad data: {e}")

print(f"Ingested: {valid_web_docs[0].metadata['title']} ({valid_web_docs[0].metadata['word_count']} words)")

Why this is critical for Web Ingestion
1. URL Safety
By using HttpUrl in Pydantic, you ensure that any "source" metadata is a valid, clickable link. If the loader accidentally grabs a relative path or a broken string, Pydantic will flag it before it reaches your database.
2. Handling Missing Titles
Many websites (especially raw text files or poorly coded sites) don't have a <title> tag. WebBaseLoader might return None. Pydantic automatically fills this with "Untitled Page", so your frontend doesn't show blank spaces.
3. Data Normalization
Websites use different language formats (e.g., en-us, en_GB, English). The field_validator in the example above shrinks all of those down to a simple en. This makes it 10x easier to filter your data later:
> Query: "Give me all documents where language is 'en'" (This only works if the data is normalized!)
> 
Comparison: The Web "Mess" vs. Pydantic
| Metadata Key | Raw WebBaseLoader | Pydantic Validated |
|---|---|---|
| source | https://example.com/path | Url('https://example.com/path') |
| title | None | "Untitled Page" |
| language | "en-US" | "en" |
| word_count | (Not provided) | 452 (Calculated & Validated) |
